n processes in contemporary Japanese, with particular emphasis on their typologically characteristic features and their interactions with syntax and semantics. Through contacts with a variety of languages over more than two thousand years of history, Japanese has developed a complex vocabulary system that is composed of four lexical strata: (i) native Japanese, (ii) mimetic, (iii) Sino-Japanese, and (iv) foreign (especially English). This hybrid composition of the lexicon, coupled with the agglutinative character of the language by which morphology is closely associated with syntax, gives rise to theoretically intriguing interactions with word formation processes that are not easily found with inflectional, isolate, or polysynthetic types of languages.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aJapanese languagexLexicologyvHandbooks, manuals, etc. 0aJapanese languagexWord formationvHandbooks, manuals, etc. 7aFOREIGN LANGUAGE STUDY / Japanese.2bisacsh  aJapanese.  aLanguage Contact.  aLexicon.  aLinguistics.1 aAkita, Kimi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIrwin, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIto, Takane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJacobsen, Wesley M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKageyama, Taro, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKageyama, Taro, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKishimoto, Hideki, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKishimoto, Hideki, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKobayashi, Hideki, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMiyamoto, Tadao, econtributor.4ctb4https